                <td>1–2</td>
                <td>5–7</td>
                <td>—</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Prospecting / cold traffic</strong></td>
                <td>1–2</td>
                <td>5–8</td>
                <td>—</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real frequency capping examples</h2>

        <h3>Example 1: Ecommerce retargeting guard rail</h3>
        <p>An ecommerce retailer running display retargeting for cart abandoners observed users viewing ads 30+ times per week before implementing any cap. The uncapped campaign burned through budget on users who had already decided not to convert. After implementing a 5-impression weekly cap, wasted spend dropped 40% while conversion rates stayed flat — the impressions beyond the fifth had generated zero additional purchases.</p>

        <h3>Example 2: SaaS brand awareness campaign</h3>
        <p>A SaaS company ran a 4-week brand awareness campaign targeting 50,000 in-market buyers. They set a monthly cap of 12 impressions per user (roughly 3 per week). This approach prioritized broad reach over audience saturation — each user saw the campaign consistently without overexposure, and brand recall lift measured 18% higher than their previous uncapped campaign.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Frequency capping vs. ad fatigue — what is the difference?</h2>
        <p>Ad fatigue is the outcome; frequency capping is the prevention. Ad fatigue occurs when an audience has seen an ad so many times that engagement drops, negative sentiment rises, and the campaign becomes actively counterproductive. Frequency capping is the proactive setting that prevents fatigue from developing in the first place.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>With frequency caps</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Budget spreads across more unique users</li>
              <li>CTR stays in the effective range</li>
              <li>Brand sentiment remains positive</li>
              <li>Retargeting pools stay fresh</li>
              <li>Performance data is interpretable</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Without frequency caps</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Small audiences receive 30+ exposures</li>
              <li>CTR declines 50%+ at high frequency</li>
              <li>74% of over-exposed users report annoyance</li>
              <li>Budget concentrates on already-converted users</li>
              <li>Retargeting campaigns create negative associations</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for frequency capping</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Start conservative, then expand.</strong> Begin at 3-5 weekly impressions for retargeting and 10-15 for awareness. After 2 weeks of data, adjust based on whether performance holds at higher frequencies for your specific audience.</li>
          <li><strong>Set different caps for different audience temperatures.</strong> High-intent retargeting audiences (viewed pricing page, added to cart) can sustain slightly higher frequency than cold prospecting audiences because their purchase likelihood per impression is higher.</li>
          <li><strong>Cap at the ad creative level, not just campaign level.</strong> If you're running 3 creative variants, a campaign-level 15-impression cap could mean 5 exposures per creative — reasonable. But if only 1 creative is winning, all 15 impressions may show the same ad.</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor frequency in your reporting dashboard weekly.</strong> Average frequency figures can mask outliers. Some users in small audiences may be hitting 20+ exposures even when the average is 5.</li>
          <li><strong>Refresh creative when caps lift is needed.</strong> If you need more exposures to hit reach goals, refreshing the creative is more effective than raising caps — new creative resets fatigue for users who have already seen the old version.</li>
          <li><strong>Account for cross-platform cumulative frequency.</strong> If you're running on 3 platforms simultaneously, assume total user exposure is roughly 3x each platform's cap. Plan accordingly.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — not setting caps on retargeting campaigns</div>
          <p>Retargeting campaigns without frequency caps are the most common source of ad fatigue. Small audience sizes (500-2,000 cart abandoners) mean impressions concentrate rapidly. Without a cap, each user in a 1,000-person retargeting pool can receive 50+ impressions per week while your budget burns through in days.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common frequency capping mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Setting caps too high on retargeting</strong> — retargeting audiences are small; higher caps mean fewer unique users reached and more money wasted on fatigue.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring cross-platform cumulative frequency</strong> — a 5-cap on 3 platforms = 15 total potential exposures per user.</li>
          <li><strong>Not refreshing creative with cap increases</strong> — raising the cap without new creative just serves fatigued ads more often.</li>
          <li><strong>Setting caps without reviewing performance data</strong> — the right cap varies by industry, audience size, and creative quality. Check actual frequency distributions, not just averages.</li>
          <li><strong>Applying the same cap to all campaign types</strong> — a 3-weekly cap works for retargeting but may limit reach for a broad awareness campaign unnecessarily.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
