            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Caps may slightly reduce total impressions. However, they improve efficiency by eliminating wasteful over-exposure. Most advertisers maintain or improve total conversions after implementing caps because budget redirects toward fresh audiences rather than over-saturating small retargeting pools.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Can I set different caps for different audiences?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yes. Most DSPs and some self-serve platforms support audience-specific caps. High-intent retargeting audiences warrant slightly higher caps than cold prospecting audiences because purchase likelihood per impression is higher for warm audiences.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What happens when ad frequency exceeds 8-10 exposures?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Research shows CTR typically declines by 50% or more once frequency exceeds 8-10 exposures per period. Simultaneously, negative brand sentiment increases — 74% of consumers report annoyance from seeing ads too frequently, which can damage future campaign effectiveness.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How do frequency caps work across platforms?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Each platform tracks impressions independently. A user can hit your 5-impression cap on Google and your 5-impression cap on Meta simultaneously, for 10 total exposures. Cross-platform frequency management requires data clean rooms or unified identity solutions — most advertisers account for this by setting lower individual platform caps.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

